    <section id="faq">
      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
      <details><summary>What's the best side hustle for a stay-at-home mom with a toddler at home?</summary><p>Pausable tasks — freelance writing, transcription, or affiliate marketing content — work best, since none of them require a scheduled call or a fixed block of uninterrupted time. Anything that requires a live call at a specific time is harder to sustain with an unpredictable toddler schedule.</p></details>
      <details><summary>Can I do a side hustle with no set schedule at all?</summary><p>Yes. Freelance writing, digital products, affiliate marketing, and content creation are all asynchronous — you work in whatever windows you have, whenever they happen, rather than committing to a shift or a scheduled call.</p></details>
      <details><summary>How much can a stay-at-home mom realistically earn from a side hustle?</summary><p>Most side hustlers in this situation earn $200–$800 a month working 10–15 hours a week. Service-based hustles with recurring clients (writing, social media management, bookkeeping) tend to scale higher over time than one-off task platforms.</p></details>
      <details><summary>Do I need childcare to start a side hustle from home?</summary><p>No — the methods in this guide are specifically chosen because they don't require dedicated childcare. Naptime-batchable and pausable work are designed around the reality of caring for children while working.</p></details>
      <details><summary>What side hustles should I avoid as a stay-at-home mom?</summary><p>Avoid anything requiring fixed live shifts (call-center scheduling, live customer service) unless you have reliable, consistent childcare during those hours — the schedule mismatch is the most common reason these arrangements fail for parents at home full-time.</p></details>
      <details><summary>Is affiliate marketing a good fit for stay-at-home moms?</summary><p>Yes — it's entirely asynchronous, requires no live availability, and content can be created in short, interrupted windows and published whenever it's finished. Income scales with audience rather than hours worked, which suits an unpredictable schedule better than hourly task work.</p></details>
    </section>

